  <div slot="about" class="editorial-content">
    <h2>Bluesky Character Counter: Real-Time Post Length Audit</h2>
    <div style="margin: 1.5rem 0; background: var(--color-bg-alt); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: var(--radius-md); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-left: 4px solid var(--color-brand);">
      <p style="margin: 0; font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        🦋 <strong>Want to master growth strategies on the Bluesky app?</strong> Read our comprehensive strategy guide on <a href="/blog/bluesky-character-counter-guide" style="color: var(--color-brand); text-decoration: underline;">Bluesky Character Limits & Thread Optimization</a> to learn how to write micro-blog copies, place link tags, and build threads.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>Introduction</h3>
    <p>
      Bluesky, a decentralized micro-blogging platform built on the AT Protocol, has emerged as a major space for real-time text updates, news sharing, and developer discussions. Unlike platforms that allow massive text boxes, Bluesky restricts posts to a strict budget of <strong>300 characters</strong>. Naming link cards, mentions, and tags within this window requires auditing characters. This free <strong>bluesky character counter</strong> makes writing drafts easy.
    </p>

    <h3>How to Use This Tool</h3>
    <p>
      To write drafts and check character counts, follow these instructions:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Input Text:</strong> Start typing or paste your post copy into the active workspace editor.</li>
      <li><strong>Review Progress:</strong> Watch the character count badge (showing X / 300) and the visual progress bar.</li>
      <li><strong>Audit Metrics:</strong> Check stats for total words, spaces, link counts, and remaining character space.</li>
      <li><strong>Live Mockup Preview:</strong> Review how your post will render in the light-themed Bluesky post mockup card.</li>
      <li><strong>Copy Draft:</strong> Click <strong>Copy Post Text</strong> to save your finished update.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>What is Bluesky Character Counter</h3>
    <p>
      A <strong>bluesky character counter</strong> or <strong>bluesky length checker</strong> is an interactive writing tool designed to verify post lengths. It counts every character (including letters, numbers, spaces, and punctuation) to make sure updates fit within Bluesky's character limit.
    </p>

    <h3>How Does It Work?</h3>
    <p>
      The tool parses text strings in real-time to generate counts:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Punctuation & Emojis:</strong> Measures emoji characters accurately (certain emojis count as multiple bytes under UTF-16, but Bluesky handles standard emojis as single characters).</li>
      <li><strong>Link Facet Audits:</strong> Counts URL lengths. Bluesky counts the exact characters of links unless converted into rich links.</li>
      <li><strong>Real-time Stats:</strong> Dynamically calculates words, whitespace counts, and links using regex matching.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Example Calculation</h3>
    <p>
      Let's look at how a Bluesky post budget is calculated:
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Draft Post Content:</strong><br />
      `"Excited to share our new design updates for creators feel! Check out the details here: creatorsfeel.com #design"`
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Character Budget Breakdown:</strong><br />
      ✦ Main Hook: `"Excited to share our new design updates for creators feel! Check out the details here: "` $\rightarrow$ <strong>86 characters</strong>.<br />
      ✦ URL Link: `"creatorsfeel.com"` $\rightarrow$ <strong>16 characters</strong>.<br />
      ✦ Hashtag: `" #design"` $\rightarrow$ <strong>8 characters</strong>.<br />
      ✦ Total Characters: `86 + 16 + 8 = 110 characters`.<br />
      ✦ Remaining characters: `300 - 110 = 190 characters`.
    </p>
    <p>
      This draft uses 110 characters, leaving a budget of 190 characters. It will publish cleanly.
    </p>

    <h3>Who Should Use This Tool?</h3>
    <p>
      This <strong>free bluesky post length tracker</strong> is designed for:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Content Creators & Writers:</strong> Keeping updates short, punchy, and formatted.</li>
      <li><strong>Social Media Managers:</strong> Reviewing scheduled updates before bulk scheduling.</li>
      <li><strong>Journalists & Publishers:</strong> Sharing news headlines and linking back to publications.</li>
      <li><strong>Developer & Tech Teams:</strong> Formatting release updates and sharing repository links.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</ToolLayout>

